    content_html: `<article class="chapter-content">
<h2>Chapter 2: Phone Scams — The Calls You Should Never Answer</h2>

<p>The telephone has been a part of American life for more than a century. For many people who grew up with it, answering the phone is almost reflexive — a social obligation, a lifelong habit. Scammers exploit this habit relentlessly. According to data from the Federal Trade Commission, phone calls remain the most common method used to target older adults in fraud schemes. More than half of all fraud complaints from people over sixty-five involve the telephone.</p>

<p>This chapter explains the most common phone scams targeting seniors in 2025 and 2026, how to recognize them in the first thirty seconds of a call, and what to do when you encounter one.</p>

<h3>Government Impersonation Calls</h3>

<p>The most feared phone scam among older adults involves someone claiming to be from a government agency — the Social Security Administration, the IRS, Medicare, or local law enforcement. These callers use official-sounding language, may have a caller ID that appears to show a real government number (a technique called "spoofing"), and claim that you are in serious legal or financial trouble.</p>

<p>A man we will call Raymond, a seventy-eight-year-old retired postal worker from Kettering, Ohio, received a call in the fall of 2024 from someone who identified themselves as a Social Security Administration inspector. The caller said that Raymond's Social Security number had been used to open fraudulent bank accounts connected to drug trafficking in Texas, that an arrest warrant was pending, and that the only way to protect his identity and avoid arrest was to immediately withdraw his savings and transfer them to a "secure federal account" the caller would provide. Raymond was so frightened that he drove to his bank and began to withdraw funds before a bank teller noticed the situation and called the police.</p>

<p>The Social Security Administration will never call you to report that your number has been misused in a criminal case. The IRS does not call to demand immediate payment. Medicare does not call to say your card has been compromised. These agencies communicate through official written mail. If you receive a call like Raymond almost did, hang up. The warrant, the criminal investigation, the compromised account — none of it is real.</p>

<h3>The "Grandparent Scam"</h3>

<p>This scam is emotionally devastating precisely because it targets the most powerful relationship most older adults have: the relationship with their grandchildren. A caller pretending to be a grandchild — or pretending to be an attorney or police officer calling on behalf of a grandchild — claims that the grandchild is in serious trouble. They have been in a car accident. They have been arrested. They are in the hospital in another city or another country and need money urgently.</p>

<p>The caller will often say, "Grandma, please don't tell Mom and Dad — I don't want them to know." This isolation request is a defining feature of this scam. It is designed to cut you off from the people most likely to tell you that something is wrong.</p>

<p>With the rise of AI voice cloning technology, some versions of this scam now use a synthesized voice that sounds remarkably like the actual grandchild — created from recordings scraped from social media. If you receive this kind of call, do not send money no matter how convincing the voice sounds. Hang up and call your grandchild directly on a number you already have saved. If you cannot reach them, call their parents. A real emergency will still be there after you have verified it. A scam will fall apart the moment you try to verify.</p>

<h3>Tech Support Scams</h3>

<p>You answer the phone and a caller says they are from Microsoft, Apple, or your internet service provider. They tell you that your computer is infected with a virus that is currently sending your banking information to criminals. They may sound very technical and convincing. They will offer to fix the problem remotely — all they need is for you to allow them to connect to your computer.</p>

<p>If you allow the connection, the caller will typically install software that gives them complete control over your computer. They will then demand payment — usually hundreds of dollars — to "fix" the problem. In many cases, they will also browse your files while connected, looking for passwords, bank account numbers, or other sensitive information.</p>

<p>Neither Microsoft, Apple, nor any internet service provider will call you out of the blue to say your computer has a virus. These companies do not monitor your computer. They do not call you. If you receive this kind of call, hang up. If you are genuinely concerned about your computer, take it to a local, reputable repair shop — not the one recommended by the caller.</p>

<h3>Lottery and Prize Scams</h3>

<p>The call or letter tells you that you have won a lottery, a sweepstakes, or a cash prize — perhaps from Publishers Clearing House, a major retailer, or an international lottery. To claim your prize, you just need to pay a small processing fee, import tax, or customs charge first. Once you pay, you will receive your winnings.</p>

<p>You will never receive the winnings. The prize does not exist. And the fees — typically requested by wire transfer, gift card, or cryptocurrency — will be gone the moment you send them. Legitimate sweepstakes and lotteries never require winners to pay anything in advance. In fact, it is illegal under U.S. law to require a purchase or payment to enter a legitimate sweepstakes. If winning something requires you to pay something first, you have not won anything.</p>

<h3>The "Grandchild Safe Word" System</h3>

<p>One of the most effective protections against impersonation scams — especially the grandparent scam — is the establishment of a family safe word. This is a word or short phrase that only your immediate family knows. If someone calls claiming to be a grandchild or family member in trouble, you ask them for the safe word. A real family member will know it. A scammer will not. Choose a word that is easy for everyone to remember but not obvious — not a birthday, not a pet's name, not something mentioned on social media. Pick something unusual and agree on it at your next family gathering.</p>

<h3>What to Do When You Receive a Suspicious Call</h3>

<ol>
<li><strong>Trust your instincts.</strong> If something feels wrong, it probably is. You do not need to be polite to someone who may be trying to steal from you.</li>
<li><strong>Hang up.</strong> You do not owe anyone an explanation. You can simply press the end call button and put the phone down.</li>
<li><strong>Do not call back the number they give you.</strong> Look up the phone number of the real organization independently — through their official website or a printed statement — and call that number instead.</li>
<li><strong>Tell a family member or friend.</strong> Even if the caller told you to keep it confidential. Especially if the caller told you to keep it confidential.</li>
<li><strong>Report the call.</strong> Contact the FTC at reportfraud.ftc.gov or call 1-877-382-4357. Your report helps law enforcement track patterns and protect others.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Chapter Warning Signs Checklist</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Caller claims to be from Social Security, IRS, Medicare, or law enforcement</li>
  <li>Caller says you must act within minutes or hours</li>
  <li>Caller asks you to pay with gift cards, wire transfer, or cryptocurrency</li>
  <li>Caller tells you not to tell anyone about the call</li>
  <li>Caller says you have won a prize but must pay a fee first</li>
  <li>Caller says your computer has a virus and offers remote help</li>
  <li>The caller ID shows an official-looking number (this can be faked)</li>
</ul>
</article>`,
