    content_html: `<article class="chapter-content">
<h2>Chapter 3: Email Phishing — Spotting the Fake</h2>

<p>Phishing is the practice of sending fraudulent emails designed to look like they come from a legitimate source — your bank, Amazon, the Social Security Administration, Medicare, PayPal, or any other trusted organization — with the goal of tricking you into clicking a link, opening an attachment, or handing over personal information. The word "phishing" comes from the idea of casting a wide net and waiting to see who bites.</p>

<p>Modern phishing emails can be extremely convincing. They use the exact logos, fonts, and language of the institutions they are imitating. They may include your name, your partial account number, or other details scraped from data breaches or public records. But even the most convincing phishing email has tells — and this chapter teaches you how to find them.</p>

<h3>The Most Common Email Scams Targeting Seniors</h3>

<p><strong>Package Delivery Notifications.</strong> You receive an email from what appears to be UPS, FedEx, or the U.S. Postal Service, saying that a package could not be delivered and that you need to click a link to reschedule delivery. The link takes you to a fake website that asks for your address, phone number, and often credit card information to pay a small "redelivery fee." If you were not expecting a package, do not click anything. If you were expecting a package, go directly to the carrier's official website by typing the address into your browser — do not click the link in the email.</p>

<p><strong>Account Verification Requests.</strong> Your bank, Amazon, Netflix, or another service sends an email saying that your account has been locked, that suspicious activity was detected, or that you need to verify your information to continue using the service. These emails almost always contain an urgent tone and a link to click. The link leads to a fake version of the real website, designed to capture your username and password when you log in.</p>

<p><strong>IRS and Tax Notices.</strong> The IRS communicates almost exclusively by postal mail. If you receive an email claiming to be from the IRS, it is fraudulent. The IRS does not send emails, does not use email to request personal information, and does not initiate contact by phone. If you receive an email claiming to be from the IRS with any kind of threat or demand, do not respond and do not click any links. Report it to phishing@irs.gov.</p>

<p><strong>Medicare and Health Insurance Notifications.</strong> You receive an email saying your Medicare benefits will be suspended, that your supplemental insurance account has been compromised, or that you are eligible for a new benefit but must verify your information immediately. Medicare communicates by mail. If you receive an email about your Medicare coverage, call 1-800-MEDICARE (1-800-633-4227) to verify whether it is real before taking any action.</p>

<h3>How to Read an Email Critically</h3>

<p>There are several simple techniques that will help you evaluate any email quickly and reliably.</p>

<p><strong>Check the sender's email address.</strong> The displayed name of the sender might say "Amazon Customer Service," but the actual email address — which you can see by clicking or hovering on the sender name — might be something like amazon-support@xrz789.net. Legitimate companies send emails from addresses at their own domain: amazon.com, usps.com, irs.gov. If the domain in the email address does not match the company's real web address, the email is fraudulent.</p>

<p><strong>Look for spelling and grammar errors.</strong> Scam emails often contain subtle errors that a professional company would never allow: misspelled words, unusual punctuation, or sentences that feel slightly off. This is not always the case with sophisticated attacks, but it is a useful filter. If an official-looking communication reads awkwardly, be suspicious.</p>

<p><strong>Hover before you click.</strong> Before clicking any link in an email, hover your mouse cursor over the link without clicking. Most email programs will show you the actual web address the link will take you to. If the address is not the official website of the company — or if it is a string of numbers or a strange domain — do not click.</p>

<p><strong>Go directly, do not click.</strong> This is the single most protective habit you can develop for email safety. Whenever you receive an email about your bank account, Amazon account, or any other service, do not click the link in the email. Instead, open your browser and type the address of the website directly — the same way you normally access it. Then log in as usual. If there is really a problem with your account, you will see a notice when you log in normally. If there is nothing unusual, the email was fraudulent.</p>

<h3>The "Dear Customer" Signal</h3>

<p>Legitimate companies that have your account information will almost always address you by name in their communications. "Dear Patricia," or "Dear Mr. Johnson." A scam email, which is often sent to millions of people at once, will typically say "Dear Customer," "Dear Account Holder," or "Dear User," because the sender does not know your name. This is not a perfect rule — some legitimate emails from large companies still use generic greetings — but "Dear Customer" combined with any kind of urgent demand or link is a strong warning sign.</p>

<h3>What to Do with a Suspicious Email</h3>

<ol>
<li><strong>Do not click any links or open any attachments.</strong> Even opening an attachment can install software on your computer.</li>
<li><strong>Do not reply.</strong> Replying confirms that your email address is active and invites more phishing attempts.</li>
<li><strong>Verify independently.</strong> If the email seems to be about a real account you have, contact the company directly using a phone number or website address you already know.</li>
<li><strong>Mark it as spam or phishing</strong> using your email provider's built-in tools. This helps train the spam filters to catch similar emails in the future.</li>
<li><strong>Delete it.</strong> Once you have confirmed it is fraudulent and reported it, delete it.</li>
</ol>

<h3>Chapter Warning Signs Checklist</h3>
<ul>
  <li>Email addresses you as "Dear Customer" or "Dear User" instead of by name</li>
  <li>Sender's email address does not match the company's real domain</li>
  <li>Email contains spelling or grammar errors</li>
  <li>Link destination (shown on hover) does not match the company's real website</li>
  <li>Email creates urgency — "act within 24 hours" or "your account will be closed"</li>
  <li>Email asks you to verify account information by clicking a link</li>
  <li>Email is from the IRS (the IRS does not email)</li>
</ul>
</article>`,
